<TEXT>
a heroic soviet helicopter pilot who developed 
leukemia after helping entomb the burning chernobyl nuclear reactor 
did not die in vain his widow said at a memorial service thursday 
galina grischenko spoke of the treatment her husband anatoly 
grischenko received at the fred hutchinson cancer research center 
where he died monday at age 53 
i think that this example of good cooperation will help all 
others who have suffered in the chernobyl disaster mrs 
grischenko said speaking through an interpreter 
about 50 hospital officials friends of mrs grischenko and 
wellwishers attended the service at a funeral home 
grischenko was among the pilots who flew helicopters over the 
damaged highly radioactive chernobyl nuclear plant for three days 
after the 1986 disaster dropping huge loads of sand and wet cement 
to encase the burning reactor 
he and several others in the operation were designated heroes of 
the soviet union that countrys highest honor 
grishchenko suffered acute radiation sickness after the disaster 
and was found to have leukemia last year because the only bone 
marrow transplant center in the soviet union could not treat him 
he was flown to seattle on april 11 a bone marrow transplant was 
performed at the cancer center later that month 
doctors reported encouraging progress after the transplant but 
grishchenkos condition worsened when a monthsold lung infection 
flared up and he had to undergo surgery june 12 he was placed on a 
respirator june 15 and died monday night 
the term hero is well applied to him dr richard 
vanderjagt said at the memorial service 
it is sometimes used loosely but certainly not with regards to 
him said vanderjagt i really do feel that anatoly was a great 
hero 
dr john hansen an associate director of the hutchinson center 
said grishchenko has helped focus renewed attention on chernobyl 
there is a lot to be done about the chernobyl disaster 
hansen said and of course there is a lot to be done about world 
peace 
grishchenkos body was to be flown back to moscow this weekend 
accompanied by mrs grishchenko and the pilots soviet physician 
dr eugenia margulis 
