hundreds of ethnic albanians from yugoslavia 
staged a protest thursday against the forced dissolution of the 
government in their region of the country calling it a prelude to 
civil war 
the protesters gathered in front of the united nations said 
authorities in yugoslavias largest republic serbia which 
controls their region of kosovo had arrested the leaders of the 
ethnic albanian democracy movement 
about 500 demonstrators who temporarily blocked traffic on 
first avenue chanted usa and democracy 
some held up the red flag of their region whose provincial 
assembly on monday declared it would secede from serbia 
the demonstration followed the suspension thursday by serbian 
authorities of all elected and other officials in kosovos local 
government 
several leading ethnic albanian officials and journalists were 
removed from their jobs at kosovos radio television and the 
albanianlanguage rilindia publishing house which publishes a 
daily newspaper 
the decision to dissolve kosovos legislature and government was 
approved unanimously by all three chambers of serbias parliament 
it came in the wake of a declaration monday by 114 ethnic albanian 
deputies in kosovos provincial assembly to secede from serbia 
according to television reports in the serbian capital of belgrade 
one of the protesters zaide gjonbalaj 15 lived in kosovo 
until last year 
a lot of people got killed they the serbs just hate our 
guts and think were animals its worse than war said 
gjonbalaj who lives in the borough of brooklyn 
she said she remembered army troops last year in the capital 
city of pristina throwing tear gas at school children including 
her 
there will for sure be a civil war said shefcet karacica 
of the borough of the bronx theyre beating children in front of 
their mothers and fathers and theyre sending in troops 
din derti vice chairman of the albanianamerican civic league 
a washingtonbased human rights group said relatives reported that 
yugoslavian police were beating citizens and making mass arrests 
an albanianlanguage manhattanbased radio station the voice 
of freedom was interviewing writer rexhep qosja from his home in 
pristina on thursday when his telephone line suddenly went dead 
the radio station later contacted the writers wife and learned 
he had been arrested 
