police in riot gear arrested about 50 people at a 
demonstration thursday by haitianamericans at a shopping center 
where last week a haitian immigrant was allegedly beaten by 
hispanic employees 
the incident occurred at the biscayne plaza shopping center when 
police began trying to disperse the crowd which swelled from about 
50 to 100 demonstrators said officer george law 
about 160 officers outfitted with nightsticks shields and 
helmets with face guards were called to the scene north of 
downtown near little haiti police said 
we told them to disperse and they failed to so we moved in 
said police spokesman roberto navarro a community cant hold 
someone hostage like that 
four of those arrested were in stable condition late thursday at 
jackson memorial hospital after treatment for minor facial cuts 
scrapes and bruises said hospital spokesman don del vecchio 
three were being held in the hospitals prison ward a fourth 
was undergoing treatment in the emergency room 
the rest of those arrested were taken to the dade county jail on 
charges including assault resisting arrest disorderly conduct and 
failure to disperse 
the protests in front of the rapid transit factory outlet store 
began june 29 after a dispute between the store owner and a 
haitianamerican customer over alterations for a pair of pants the 
customer abner alezi claimed he was beaten 
alezi 44 and several others were later arrested for 
trespassing when they returned to the store to complain 
when store owner luis reyes tried to open the store on saturday 
more than 1000 haitians turned out in a peaceful protest the 
store then remained closed until thursday 
police chief perry anderson said his department had tried to 
mediate the dispute 
we are being extremely tolerant anderson said there have 
been rocks and bottles thrown for two days the owner of the store 
has been held hostage we have been very very tolerant 
at least 40 officers remained at the store late thursday 
reyes said he planned to reopen his store friday 
we are here to do business and to set a principle that not us 
not any merchant and not the city of miami police department will 
be intimidated by something like this said reyes a 65yearold 
cubanamerican the violence will not take over 
the fracas left protesters shoes coats and hats strewn across 
the rainy parking lot 
the confrontation at the shopping center followed tension 
between blacks and hispanics over the recent visit of south african 
