<TEXT>
despite working three jobs a 
28yearold albanian asylumseeker says he just cant make a 
living in his communist homeland and wants to go anywhere that 
offers the promise of a better life 
he is one of the nearly 600 albanians who have sought refuge in 
foreign embassies in tirana this week in a desperate bid to flee 
the country 
the 28yearold interviewed thursday by telephone by hungarian 
state radio is holed up with 11 other albanians in the hungarian 
embassy one of a dozen foreign embassies in tirana where 
albanians have sought asylum 
i came here because i just cant make a living he said i 
am 28 i have a wife and two children i work as a bricklayer as a 
driver and as a lathe operator the man said speaking in his 
native albanian his comments were translated into hungarian 
it was not clear from the interview whether his family had fled 
with him to the embassy he did not explain why he chose to seek 
refuge in the hungarian embassy 
i make 400 leks about 57 dollars a month said the 
asylumseeker who was not identified by name 
he said rent and electricty cost more than 50 leks a month a 
22 pounds of bread cost four leks a quart of milk three leks and 
a kilogram of sugar eight leks 
everything is very expensive here or rather we earn very 
little he told the radio it is impossible to make a decent 
living 
with the fall of communist leaders in hungary and most other 
eastern european countries albania remains the last bastion of 
orthodox communism in europe its leaders have begun to implement 
some cautious reforms such as allowing citizens to apply for 
passports to travel abroad 
but the 28yearold asylumseeker said that even if he were 
granted a passport under the new regulations he doesnt have 
enough money to pay for a trip abroad 
even if they would now give me a passport i do not have the 
money for plane fare but i promise to work very hard and pay it 
all back he said 
the albanian told hungarian radio that he would like to go to 
italy west germany or the united states anywhere just away 
from here 
