<TEXT>
president bush gave an important but little 
noticed speech on hemispheric policy last week what set it apart 
from virtually every other presidential initiative for the americas 
over the past two generations was that it had nothing to do with 
fighting communism 
this week bush is attending the first postcold war nato summit 
and last weeks speech showed that with eastwest tensions in 
decline he now has the luxury of giving priority to the 
hemispheres economic troubles as opposed to security concerns 
bush said that to bolster the hemispheres newly emerging 
democracies there is need for more trade and investment and 
additional debt relief 
the speech was a departure from past initiatives which had the 
underlying rationale of keeping marxism out of the hemisphere 
the list is long there was the ciainitiated coup in guatemala 
in 1954 the americansponsored invasion of cuba in 1961 and the 
creation of the ambitious social and economic development program 
called the alliance for progress that same year 
there was the cuban missile crisis of 1962 the us military 
intervention in the dominican republic in 1965 and the efforts to 
undercut chiles leftist government from 197073 hemispheric 
policy during the reagan years was devoted largely to combating 
leftist forces in central america the caribbean basin initiative 
of the early 1980s was partly a response to leftist gains 
bushs new proposal is aimed at reversing the economic decline 
that afflicted much of latin america during the 1980s he offered 
some debt relief and promised to open the united states to more 
hemispheric exports if us goods are granted the same treatment 
the ultimate aim he said is a free trade system that links 
all of the americas north central and south and we look 
forward to the day when not only are the americas the first fully 
free democratic hemisphere but when all are equal partners in a 
free trade zone stretching from the port of anchorage to the tierra 
del fuego 
a long hard effort lies ahead but susan kaufman purcell of the 
americas society believes it is well worthwhile she points out 
that us exporters could benefit greatly from a market 
encompassing 435 million people 
ms purcell says latin americans have been worried about being 
ignored as a result of the end of the cold war as a result she 
says there is a new receptivity among latin americans for closer 
ties with the united states 
a hemispheric free trade zone is therefore an idea whose time 
has come ms purcell writes 
the washington post editorialized last friday that bushs 
proposal could bring immense benefits to latin american countries 
where closed economies and protection of monopolies have created 
great wealth for a few people at the top and great poverty for 
the rest 
opening up these economies will be bad for the monopolies but 
very good for the middle class and the people trying to climb into 
it the post said 
reaction to the bush proposal has been almost universally 
favorable in latin america the contrast in attitudes toward the 
united states during the 1980s is considerable those were the days 
when reagan administration tried mightily to enlist hemispheric 
support behind its policy of arming the nicaraguan contras but to 
little avail 
with nicaragua no longer an issue and communism less of a 
concern to washington many believe the prospects for a productive 
uslatin american relationship seem brighter than at any time in 
years 
the interamerican dialogue a gathering of 50 leaders from 
throughout the americas said bushs initiative is welcome 
timely and potentially significant indeed it could mark a turning 
point in interamerican relations if it is now turned from a 
broad vision to concrete and joint actions 
</TEXT>
