<TEXT>
thousands of florida inmates have been 
barred from workrelease programs after a convicted murderer 
escaped from a community detail and allegedly stabbed a woman to 
death in a mall 
the new prison policy means 50 percent of the entire prison 
population of 42700 inmates will be held in the states most 
secure prisons about 40 percent or 18127 were in such prisons 
before the new policy was announced by gov bob martinez thursday 
martinez said the old system was antiquated and allowed 
prison officials too much discretion in deciding whether hardcore 
criminals could get assigned to work details for community jobs 
road work and prison industries 
we cant stop every criminal from committing criminal acts 
he said but we can stop giving the worst of them the opportunity 
to walk the streets of our communities where they have the 
greatest chance to escape and threaten lawabiding citizens 
about 3400 inmates now classified for minimum or 
mediumsecurity institutions will be shifted to more secure 
socalled closecustody prisons and it will be more difficult for 
violent or longterm inmates to get into workrelease programs 
martinez blamed the old policy for donald david dillbecks 
escape on june 22 from a catering detail out of the quincy 
vocational center 
dillbeck convicted of the 1979 murder of a lee county sheriffs 
deputy is charged with fatally stabbing 44yearold faye lamb vann 
on june 24 as she sat in her car at a tallahassee mall 
three corrections officials were fired for letting dillbeck into 
the program and onto the catering detail 
the judgment was faulty no question martinez said but 
the discretion allowed to corrections officials led the fault to 
occur 
eight other prison officials involved in the dillbeck case will 
not be fired martinez said but remain on administrative leave 
pending possible department disciplinary action 
the case became a political issue when former sen lawton 
chiles a candidate in the democratic primary for governor blamed 
it on prison policies of martinez whose reelection campaign touts 
his lawandorder record 
the old rules let those prisoners required to serve a specific 
sentence before being eligible for parole to be moved to 
lesssecure custody status after they finished 40 percent of their 
mandatory sentences dillbeck for instance had served 44 percent 
of his 25yearminimum term 
the new policy requires that all such inmates serve the entire 
minimum portion of their sentences in close custody before they can 
be assigned to a workrelease program 
inmates will be ineligible for workrelease or other community 
jobs if they have been convicted of first or seconddegree murder 
unless they are within one year of release and have served all 
mandatory time 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

