<TEXT>
more than 150 wildfires raced across 
alaskas interior forcing the evacuation of a town of 900 people 
and disrupting travel on highways choked by heat and smoke 
gov steve cowper declared a statewide state of emergency and 
called on the alaska national guard to help fight the fires that 
raged over 270 square miles of forest and open tundra an elite 
firefighting team from california was being flown in later today 
no injuries were reported 
the biggest fire covered about 47 square miles near beaver 
about 110 miles north of fairbanks but no structures were 
threatened there 
the greater threat was a wildfire that took only 24 hours to 
nearly double in size to at least 39 square miles today flames 
swelled up over trees and drew to within a quarter mile of the east 
edge of tok a town about 175 miles southeast of fairbanks 
emergency workers thursday afternoon went door to door urging 
people to leave their homes the evacuation remained in effect 
early today 
authorities closed portions of the glenn highway leading south 
to anchorage and the alaska highway a main road from the canada 
border for the day thursday but the smoke hazard diminished 
overnight and traffic resumed 
state troopers said there was a steady line of cars passing 
through tok early today many were tourists hauling campers who 
spent the night camped at the village airstip 
more than 400 firefighters spent thursday cutting firebreaks and 
dumping loads of chemical retardant on the crackling forests from 
airplanes flying through thick smoke a fresh crew of about 150 
arrived at fairbanks early this morning 
sharon wilson an interagency fire spokeswoman in fairbanks 
said a shift in the wind helped firefighters keep damage to almost 
zero in tok 
only a few abandoned buildings burned she said adding that 
todays work would center on widening breaks that are keeping fire 
from a neighborhood north of town 
its not moving now at any drastic rate wilson said the 
fire tends to get more quiet at night but the problem is the 
forecast is for more hot and dry weather and a possible 
thunderstorm 
the fire burned mainly black spruce birch aspen and brush on 
the flat terrain around the town some tok residents wore masks to 
filter out smoke 
whats bothering us the most is breathing theres burnt 
spruce needles falling out of the air said one resident mellie 
terwilliger you can see but you go around with your lights on 
earlier reports that the towns coast guard navigational station 
had been burned were incorrect said sue mitchell a spokeswoman 
for the bureau of land management in fairbanks the evacuated 
station which provides electronic signals to guide aviators and 
mariners only lost power she said 
seventeen firefighter managers from california were expected to 
arrive at tok later today a similar team battled the yellowstone 
national park fire that claimed more than a million acres in the 
summer of 1988 
on thursday state forester bob dick said the fire is out of 
control were throwing everything at it we have tankers 
bulldozers people and it isnt working 
the governor who flew over the region thursday said we had 
to get upwind of it before we could actually see it the fires are 
that massive 
most of the fires were blamed on heat low humidity and a rash 
of lightning strikes the fire danger was extremely high in much of 
alaska mitchell said temperatures approached 90 degrees 
throughout much of the interior wednesday 
the heat dries out alaskas forests and gives rise to late 
afternoon thunderstorms and wind gusts mitchell said there were 
more than 1800 lightning strikes in alaska on tuesday and a 
record 2192 on sunday 
on the kenai peninsula however drizzle and temperatures in the 
40s and 50s helped firefighters curb a series of blazes that broke 
out near ninilchik all the blazes there were expected to be 
contained by saturday 
nearly four dozen fires were being ignored by firefighting crews 
because of their limited ability to respond mitchell said 
