<TEXT>
the possible exposure of 120 people to a 
fatal leukemia virus was an unacceptable break in procedure but 
probably didnt put anyone at serious risk university of 
pennsylvania officials said 
about 20 veterinary students and staff and 100 visiting 
preschool children unknowingly handled 14 newborn lambs that had 
been inoculated with a slowacting virus htlv1 the human tcell 
lymphotropic virus can cause a lethal form of leukemia in people 
but does not grow in sheep 
it was an unacceptable break of procedure said penns vice 
provost for research barry cooperman 
he said many of the veterinary school researchers expressed 
concern that allegations of misconduct would damage the public 
perception of science and hinder research efforts 
the universitys concern is that the public puts its trust in 
us he said we owe the public scrupulous responsibility in 
conducting experiments 
penn officials investigating the violation are now waiting for 
test results of blood samples from those people exposed to the 
animals to determine if they were infected according to cooperman 
the exposure occurred sometime in april when the lambs were 
inoculated but not separated from the rest of their flock at penns 
600acre new bolton center in suburban chester county 
both the schools environmental health and safety office and the 
institutional animal care and use committee had specified that the 
inoculated lambs should be isolated from the rest of the flock 
it was a serious breach of responsibility said dr aron b 
fisher chairman of penns animal care committee 
cooperman said officials investigating the problem did not learn 
until early june that the veterinary students had worked with the 
lambs and that children from the kennett square cooperative 
preschool had visited the site and played with the animals 
because htlv1 is transmitted only through blood mothers milk 
and sexual intercourse school and health officials believe it is 
unlikely that anyone was infected 
the risk to children is essentially nil said cooperman 
and to our own people a minimal risk 
the experiment which was approved by a faculty committee was 
conducted by jorge f ferrer 58 a senior penn researcher ferrer 
whose research has been suspended pending the outcome of the 
inquiry has 15 days to respond 
cooperman said the school completed a preliminary investigation 
june 22 and will begin a fullscale inquiry soon he refused to 
comment on the initial findings 
ferrers telephone number is unpublished and he could not be 
reached for comment his attorney john m myers did not return 
telephone calls 
cooperman said ferrer was trying to grow the virus in the lambs 
to see if he could produce a protein that might help fight the 
virus in people 
