<TEXT>
a war on a bothersome insect called the 
ash whitefly is being broadened with squadrons of tiny stingless 
wasps from the mediterranean 
the flies have no natural enemies in california and are a 
nuisance to residents and a potential threat to the agriculture 
industry the state department of food and agriculture said they 
were first detected in california in august 1988 in los angeles 
county and have since been spotted in 17 counties and as far north 
as sacramento 
the tiny insects suck out plant juices infesting a variety of 
trees and shrubs including apple apricot citrus and pear they 
can defoliate trees and clouds of the insects have driven residents 
from their back yards 
now tiny encarsia wasps imported from israel and italy are 
being released and will be monitored to see how well they control 
the ash whiteflies 
the wasp controls the ash whitefly population by laying its eggs 
inside fly larvae after the wasps eggs hatch they eat their way 
out of the larvae killing the pest 
pesticides are not considered practical for use against the 
whitefly because the pests numbers are so large and it dwells on 
the undersides of leaves 
six southern california counties have been targeted for 
widespread release of the wasps said peter stoddard senior 
environmental research scientist with the state department of food 
and agriculture additional counties will get the wasps later this 
summer 
one of the initial sites chosen for release of the wasps was the 
fullerton arboretum on the edge of the california state university 
fullerton campus just southeast of los angeles hundreds of wasps 
were released there thursday 
wasps for future release are being reproduced at the university 
of california riverside and the rate of reproduction will 
determine how quickly other sites will receive them stoddard said 
a tiny ladybird beetle imported last year from israel also is 
being studied as a possible weapon against the fly 
california also is waging a battle against the mediterranean 
fruit fly using the pesticide malathion 
</TEXT>
