police arrested five people this morning as 
the city began enforcing a ban on sleeping in parks in an effort to 
empty a downtown plaza where more than 200 people have camped out 
for two years 
authorities said keith mchenry an activist who is one of the 
most vocal critics of the homeless removal plan was arrested 
before 6 am after about 20 officers began clearing the 
treeshaded civic center plaza four other people all 
unidentified were arrested later 
police encountered no violence sgt john goldberg said 
as an alternative to arrest for violating the public sleeping 
ban police offered vouchers for admittance to two new city 
shelters 
thursday evening a group of 50 activists and homeless people at 
the civic center decided to accept the citys offer the group 
noisily marched seven blocks to one of two new shelters where a 
worker told them all the rooms were filled 
city officials said the homeless could obtain vouchers for free 
shelter elsewhere but the group returned to the plaza a park 
surrounded by mostly government buildings 
theres no room said a homeless woman lima rashida we 
have no place to go but back to the civic center 
police had been under orders to begin making arrests at 
midnight but after the homeless marchers were faced with no 
shelter space officers on the scene did not immediately intervene 
of the five people arrested later in the morning three were 
booked on misdemeanor counts of illegal lodging and interfering 
with police and mchenry and one other person was cited with 
illegal distribution of food police said 
the march came after a peaceful candlelight vigil mourning the 
death of mitch snyder a homeless activist in washington dc who 
was found hanged thursday in what police said was an apparent 
suicide 
the homeless people in the plaza said they paid for a red white 
and blue wreath by selling jewelry and other personal items 
police capt dennis martel said the plaza transients dont 
have the option to stay here anymore we are encouraging them to go 
to the shelters were handling this in a sensible humane 
fashion 
all this week vouchers for rooms have been handed out but many 
of those living in the park expressed no interest 
im safer in this park than in one of those hotline rooms 
said a woman who identified herself as jack howard she pledged to 
stay in the plaza until police begin moving the homeless out 
the hotline rooms are hotel rooms the city has available 
howard says occupants are often bothered by crack dealers rats and 
mice 
as a woman howard does not have access to the two maleonly 
multiservice shelters the city took over this week 
the shelters operated for the city by church groups combine 
shelter with such services as drug and alcohol treatment and job 
counseling 
we have to have compassion because a lot of these people have 
had a lot of misfortune in their lives said police officer harry 
soulette as he walked around the plaza we want to help them 
being turned away from the shelter reinforced what homeless 
activists have said since the plan was revealed by mayor art agnos 
that the city simply doesnt have enough beds 
homeless advocates also charge that the cleanup program 
forced 215 people already staying in one of the two shelters out on 
