the federal judge who presided over 
courtmandated efforts to desegregate pulaski county public schools 
for eight years stepped down friday 
in an order in which he announced his decision to leave the 
case us district judge henry woods lamented the plight of black 
students in the county and criticized the federal appeals court for 
stifling his orders 
woods 72 said he was leaving because he was unable to 
successfully implement a plan to bring educational equity to the 
children of the county under the restrictions imposed by the 
appeals court 
perhaps the application of a fresh mind and the perspective of 
another judge can find hope in a situation which i perceive as 
hopeless he said 
woods will continue to hear his full slate of cases 
it has been my intention to oversee a progressive educational 
plan to serve the children of these districts into the 21st 
century such a plan would bring peace to a community long plagued 
with a worldwide reputation for racial problems in its public 
schools woods said however i have steadfastly resisted the 
notion of peaceatanyprice 
woods decision follows a ruling monday by a threejudge panel 
of the 8th us circuit of appeals ordering the release of portions 
of the 129 million settlement of the states liability in the case 
woods presided over the case involving a federal suit filed in 
1982 by the little rock school district against the pulaski county 
and north little rock districts and the state department of 
education the little rock district sought consolidation with the 
other districts in the county to achieve racial balance 
woods criticized mondays order noting that the three pulaski 
county districts have maintained that they are not required to 
spend the money solely for desegregation purposes he said the 
districts will have received and spent tens of millions of 
dollars by the time the full order of the court is issued in the 
fall 
the district court will be left trying to implement a 
longterm desegregation plan yet to be announced with 
insufficient funds remaining to implement any meaningful plan he 
said 
the appeals court this week also hinted it would limit the 
metropolitan supervisors post the office woods set up to direct 
the districts desegregation efforts to merely monitoring those 
efforts 
