<TEXT>
the nations unemployment rate edged downward 
to 52 percent last month despite an ongoing slide in manufacturing 
and overall weakness in job growth the government reported friday 
fewer americans looking for work not any rebound in sluggish 
economic activity accounted for the improvement over mays 
jobless rate of 53 percent analysts said 
its not that more people are getting jobs fewer guys are 
looking said elliott platt an economist with donaldson lufkin 
amp jenrette securities corp of new york 
the economy added just 40000 jobs to nonfarm payrolls in june 
the labor department said 
however that figure would be closer to 97000 if the temporary 
census workers the federal government laid off in june were not 
included in the count the agency said 
for the first six months of 1990 private sector businesses have 
been adding about 110000 jobs a month or about half the 220000 
average jobs gain for the same period last year the government 
said 
theres no real zip in this economy but you dont have the 
combination of recessionary forces to drag it into negative 
territory either platt said 
the reports evidence of continued softness at a time when 
unemployment is still relatively low provides a puzzling picture 
for the federal reserve which has been under pressure to lower 
interest rates analysts said 
the fed is in a quandary now from the job creation side its 
a clear case for the fed to ease but with unemployment so low 
its a very tough call said allen sinai chief economist at the 
boston co 
sinai said junes job growth figures demonstrate that the 
economy is as close to a recession configuration as we can get 
without being in one 
revised figures for may showed that about 155000 new jobs were 
added that month excluding census workers up from the original 
report of just 19000 jobs the labor department said 
unemployment has been fluctuating within a tenth of a percentage 
point of 53 percent for more than a year after hitting a 15year 
low of 5 percent in march 1989 
the rate has managed to stay relatively low despite weak job 
growth because smaller numbers of americans are entering the labor 
force said janet norwood commissioner of the bureau of labor 
statistics 
so far this year only about 290000 americans have entered the 
work force compared with the 15 million americans who joined the 
labor force during the first half of 1989 mrs norwood said the 
labor force is defined as americans who are working or actively 
seeking jobs 
the nations manufacturing sector which has been on a downward 
spiral for months continued its slide in june as factory payrolls 
fell by 31000 jobs it was the 14th time in 15 months that 
manufacturing jobs declined 
since reaching a postrecession peak in march 1989 about 
335000 factory jobs have been lost 
the number of construction jobs fell in june for the fourth 
month in a row reflecting continued weakness in the housing 
market the government said construction payrolls after seasonal 
adjustment dropped 14000 
meanwhile the service sector which has been providing most of 
the economys steam over the past several months added 83000 
jobs including 40000 in the health services industry 
retail trade businesses lost 7000 jobs in june bringing the 
monthly increases in the first half of this year in that sector to 
15000 half the average for 1989 
general merchandise stores have been particularly hard hit in 
that sector losing 50000 jobs over the past year mrs norwood 
said 
the number of discouraged workers people who want a job but 
have given up looking averaged about 900000 for the april to may 
period an increase of nearly 150000 over the first quarter of 
1990 the agency said 
that increase brought the number of discouraged workers to its 
highest level since the end of 1988 
labor costs which have been pushing up and are being blamed for 
fueling the nations inflation problems continued to increase 
average hourly earnings posted a 03 percent rise in june to 
1001 up from the 998 the average worker earned per hour in may 
the average manufacturing work week was unchanged from may at 
410 hours manufacturing overtime held at 38 hours in june 
in a separate calculation of unemployment that counts members of 
the armed services stationed in the united states the june jobless 
rate was 51 percent down from 53 percent in may and the same as 
junes civilian rate 
</TEXT>
