<TEXT>
the bush administration said friday it is 
planning to enhance current seafood inspections with a voluntary 
program paid for by companies whose products could earn an official 
government seal 
the new program would use industry controls and government 
inspections to provide additional assurances to consumers that 
fish and fish products are safe wholesome and properly labeled 
officials said 
the program was proposed by the food and drug administration and 
the national oceanic and atmospheric administration 
the fda has a seafood inspection program that requires 
examinations of processors shippers packers and repackers 
labelers warehouses and importers of fish and fish products that 
program would continue separately 
noaas national marine fisheries service runs a voluntary 
feeforservice seafood inspection program which uses a government 
inspection mark that program would continue to provide grading 
services but continuation of other parts of the program would 
depend on the extent to which companies switch to the new system 
officials said 
the new plan would be based on inspections at various critical 
points at which health risks such as spoilage and bacterial 
growth can be controlled the fda said companies would pay a fee 
for inspections and could earn an official mark or seal they could 
display on their products label 
the fda said a twomonth pilot study is scheduled to begin oct 
1 to identify problems industry and government might have in 
implementing such a system the agencies are looking for industry 
volunteers for the study 
public voice for food and health policy a consumer group 
criticized the plans saying the government should instead 
strengthen its mandatory inspection system 
its like putting a bandaid on a festering sore said ellen 
haas executive director of the group 
its a totally inadequate response to a serious public health 
problem she said what consumers need is not a voluntary 
program paid for by those fish companies that chose to participate 
but a mandatory healthbased inspection program such as ones being 
considered in congress 
</TEXT>
