<TEXT>
the agriculture department said friday it is 
seeking an alternative way of setting minimum prices paid dairy 
farmers under federal marketing orders 
the department currently uses a base known as the 
minnesotawisconsin or mw price an average of prices paid to 
farmers in the twostate area for grade b milk used only for 
manufacturing products such as cheese butter and nonfat dry milk 
daniel d haley administrator of the departments agricultural 
marketing service said the mw base price has been used since the 
early 1960s and is widely accepted as a measure of change in the 
supply and demand for milk nationally 
but a continuing decline in the output of grade b milk partly 
because of tighter sanitary standards is gradually making the mw 
price unusable for setting milk prices he said 
haley said the departments national agricultural statistics 
service which compiles the mw price questions whether it will be 
able to do so after mid1992 
the dairy industry has asked usda to develop and test 
alternative methods and a national hearing on all federal milk 
orders has been tentatively set for september although no specific 
date and location have been announced 
haley said a separate hearing on the base price will be held 
later 
meanwhile specific proposals can be sent by july 25 to 
director dairy division ams usda room 2968s po box 96456 
washington dc 200906456 
