<TEXT>
the summit stage moved friday to president bushs 
hometown where leaders of the worlds seven largest industrialized 
nations will turn their attention to the economic configuration of 
the postcold war world 
houston was turned out in the summit nations colors flags 
sprouted on downtown skyscrapers and at the rice university summit 
site painters hurried to put the finishing touches on sprucedup 
buildings 
last years summit in paris adjourned early when the leaders ran 
out of things to talk about thats not likely to happen next week 
questions of direct economic aid to the soviets a contentious 
fight over farm subsidies and problems of global pollution were 
expected to dominate the negotiating sessions and working dinners 
which get under way monday 
on many of the issues the united states found itself at odds 
with the other summit countries japan west germany france 
britain italy and canada 
in many ways the houston meeting will be a continuation of the 
talks thursday and friday at the nato summit in london of the 
seven leaders only japans prime minister toshiki kaifu did not 
participate in the nato meeting 
as his first order of business bush was to hold private talks 
with kaifu on saturday officials said that in addition to briefing 
kaifu on the outcome of the nato meeting the two leaders would 
cover the various economic issues coming up in houston 
high on the economic agenda will be the question of whether the 
west should supply a 15 billion to 20 billion aid package to bail 
out soviet president mikhail gorbachevs floundering economic 
reform effort an idea being pushed by west german chancellor 
helmut kohl and french president francois mitterrand 
bush repeated his objections to such aid on friday saying he 
has big problems in giving us assistance as long as moscow is 
spending billions of dollars annually in support for cuba but he 
appeared to open the door slightly to the possibility of extending 
some types of financial credits to the soviets 
diplomatic sources said that gorbachev had written an appeal for 
economic aid to british prime minister margaret thatcher who like 
bush is against the proposal until the soviets do more to reform 
their economy 
canadian prime minister brian mulroney predicted the economic 
summit would make substantial progress in resolving the soviet 
aid dispute 
however the most likely outcome was a vague statement of 
support which would not commit any specific amounts of money but 
would allow countries such as west germany to offer their own aid 
packages 
bush has told reporters that his top priority at the economic 
summit would be breaking a logjam on agriculture trade which has 
deadlocked an effort to reform the rules governing world trade 
the united states is pushing for agreement to phase out all 
tradedistorting farm subsidies over the next 10 years but that 
idea has drawn strong opposition from european countries whose 
leaders contend that such a proposal would cost the jobs of between 
2 million and 3 million european farmers 
the trade liberalization talks known as the uruguay round for 
the country where they were launched in 1986 are scheduled to 
conclude in december but us officials fear they could falter 
without agreement on the agriculture question 
the world leaders are also expected to consider a european 
proposal to cut back on greenhouse gases forms of pollution 
which scientists fear are trapping too much heat from the sun and 
causing global climate changes 
the us position is that more needs to be known about the 
possible threat before committing billions of dollars to cleanup 
efforts 
before all the serious talks begin the world leaders will be 
treated to a taste of texas on sunday night complete with a rodeo 
barbecue and a performance by the grand ol opry 
houston a city that suffered through hard times during the oil 
price bust of the 1980s raised 10 million in donations and 
assembled an army of volunteers to showcase houstons economic 
resurrection for the expected 3000 reporters from around the world 
on friday painters were still at work in one of the meeting 
rooms to be used during the three days of talks at rice university 
a 4000student private university five miles from downtown 
in deference to houstons notorious summer weather the outdoor 
arrival ceremony on monday was shortened and a special platform was 
constructed to pipe cool air underneath the dignataries seats 
