<TEXT>
negotiations will resume next week on final 
details of an agreement expanding us access to military 
facilities in singapore the pentagon said friday 
the proposed deal would not give the united states its own 
military base in singapore but it would greatly expand us 
military activity in the southeast asian citystate said lt cmdr 
edward h lundquist a pentagon spokesman 
lundquist said no us planes or ships would be based there 
permanently but a small contingent of american military personnel 
probably fewer than 200 would be stationed at the singapore 
facilities to keep them ready for us use 
lundquist stressed that the proposed use of singapore military 
facilities would not be a substitute for the larger us forces at 
clark air base and subic bay naval base in the philippines a 
military bases agreement between the united states and the 
philippines expires next year and the bush administration is 
seeking to negotiate some form of continued use of those facilities 
if the singapore deal is concluded us f16 fighter planes 
based elsewhere in asia would be allowed to conduct occasional 
training missions in singapore and navy ships could use 
singapores strategically located port lundquist said 
the negotiations began early this year after singapore prime 
minister lee kuan yew offered to permit greater us access to his 
countrys military facilities 
the los angeles times reported in fridays editions that it was 
possible that a final agreement would be signed when secretary of 
state james a baker iii visits singapore in august 
lundquist said he could not say how close the two sides were to 
final agreement but that the remaining issues were mainly legal 
technicalities he said a new round of talks was scheduled for next 
wednesday through friday in washington 
lundquist said the main outstanding issue was the legal status 
of american military personnel who would be stationed in singapore 
under the agreement one open question he said was what rights 
the americans would have in the event they were arrested on 
criminal charges singapore authorizes the death penalty for 
convicted drug traffickers 
singapore has one of the worlds largest harbors it lies in the 
strategic waterway through which japan and south korea get most of 
their oil from the persian gulf 
singapore is a member of the association of southeast asian 
nations a regional organization whose other members are thailand 
the philippines malaysia indonesia and brunei 
the philippines is the only asean member hosting a permanent 
us military base 
