<TEXT>
leaders of the nations largest teachers 
union focused attention friday on ways to improve the training of 
americas future educators 
don cameron national education association executive director 
said a teacher education reform initiative will begin in november 
to link universities and colleges of education with local school 
districts so innovative curriculum ideas and teaching techniques 
can be tried out in classrooms 
too often teacher education programs seem rooted in the 
rarified air of academia rather than in the realities of the 
classroom he said 
cameron said negotiations are under way with several colleges 
and universities including the university of maryland eastern 
michigan university the university of delaware several 
traditionally black institutions in the south and three colleges in 
tennessee 
many school districts are enthusiastic about the idea said 
cameron 
the program will be coordinated by sharon robinson director of 
the nea national center for innovation she said the center will 
see that teacher education programs make sure future teachers can 
effectively use new classroom technologies such as computers and 
that their training includes the latest findings in educational 
research 
future teachers must be better prepared to help all their 
student think for themselves said cameron almost everybody 
agrees students must be better taught to analyze synthesize and 
use knowledge 
the announcement came one day after the 8100 nea delegates 
abandoned opposition to socalled alternative or nontraditional 
teacher certification and agreed to allow scientists 
mathematicians and other midcareer professionals to teach while 
receiving the training needed to obtain a license 
the initiative will not seek to impose any one particular 
model for teacher preparation on schools of education said 
cameron pointing to thursdays action as proof there can be many 
roads to licensure without the sacrifice of high standards 
arthur wise president of the national council for the 
accreditation of teacher education said about 200000 teachers are 
hired each year and the reform initiative should strengthen their 
preparation for the classroom 
wise said many of the criticisms of current programs are that 
they do not adequately prepare teachers academically and fail to 
provide rigorous teacher training or classroom methods 
before wrapping up its convention in boston this week the 
american federation of teachers announced a similar program 
officials selected los angeles minneapolis and rochester ny as 
sites for helping educators determine the best ways for student 
teachers to learn new skills that can be adapted to restructured 
schools 
each site selected from among proposals submitted jointly by 
teachers unions school districts and universities will receive a 
oneyear grant of about 30000 from the exxon education foundation 
for planning and preparation 
