<TEXT>
an agriculture department task force reported 
friday that licensed dog dealers the government has investigated in 
the midwest have not knowingly engaged in selling stolen animals to 
research laboratories 
but two dealers may be prosecuted for falsifying records said 
james w glosser administrator of the departments animal and 
plant health inspection service 
after tracing many cases of sales of dogs to dealers no 
evidence was found to indicate dealers were knowingly buying stolen 
animals glosser said however the task force did find 
evidence indicating that two dealers may have falsified records and 
that 29 individuals were dealing in the wholesale movement of dogs 
without the required license 
the agency is considering prosecution of these licensed 
dealers and has issued warnings to those without licenses he 
said 
no names or locations of the animal dealers were released by the 
agency 
the investigation began in april in response to allegations from 
private individuals human groups and pet organizations that stolen 
pet dogs in the midwest were being sold to research institutions 
through usdalicensed class b dealers 
those include dealers who buy and resell animals for regulated 
purposes 
although the investigation began with licensed dog dealers in 
missouri and arkansas additional dealers were added in illinois 
indiana and tennessee for possible investigation glosser said 
the task force also contacted state police and county sheriffs 
offices for possible leads on stolen dogs he said 
federal law the animal welfare act requires every federal 
licensed or registered business institution or agency to record 
the name and address of every person from whom it buys a dog or cat 
each dog and cat must have an identity number and description 
newly acquired animals must be held for five business days to 
facilitate tracing lost or stolen animals 
