<TEXT>
president bush probably will not make a final 
decision this year on the development of an antipoverty program 
an administration official said friday 
it could well go into next year before any final decisions are 
made said a white house official who spoke only on condition of 
anonymity 
the news drew differing reactions from two experts asked by the 
white house to offer suggestions for shaping a federal antipoverty 
policy 
isabell v sawhill of the urban institute said the 
administration went through a lot of effort and came up with a 
mouse in its slow approach to dealing with poverty 
but douglas j besharov of the conservative american enterprise 
institute defended the administration saying bush was just not 
coming forward and saying i have a new program that will solve 
all the problems 
besharov and sawhill were among outside experts summoned to the 
white house in september for a meeting on the poverty issue 
thirtytwo million americans live in poverty as defined by the 
government the issue had been studied by an interagency group 
convened last year and more recently by the administrations 
domestic policy council 
the official who spoke anonymously said you may see in the 
shorter term some decisions that give an indication of the 
direction we are headed in but there will be no final decisions 
for quite some time 
deputy white house press secretary stephen hart confirmed that 
bush is waiting before deciding how to structure a program 
certainly no final decisions on what options should be 
considered by the president have been made this is a longterm 
process he said 
sawhill said however that she was frankly quite disappointed 
that they could not agree on an overall strategy 
there were a lot of good ideas put forward both from people 
who were consulted externally and also within the 
administration she added i think it was a serious and worthy 
effort but it seems to have fallen victim to some combination of 
ideology and budgetary pressures 
but besharov said that while some people might be disappointed 
by the administrations position he believes the administration is 
in the process of a longterm examination of what could be done 
and waiting to unveil a program is probably the wisest thing to 
do at this point 
he added what is important is to improve the programs that 
are in place 
besharov said a number of proposals were considered during the 
administrations deliberations 
they included 
having the government help residents of poor areas establish 
management corporations that would fight crime attempt to 
improve schools and repair housing 
allocating a larger share of federal aid to highpoverty areas 
providing financial subsidies to job contractors to help them 
match up applicants from high poverty areas with job openings 
