<TEXT>
time is running out for farmers to refund up 
to 400 million in advance crop subsidies they received from the 
federal government in 1988 and 1989 when they were hit by drought 
the oftdelayed deadline for giving back the advance deficiency 
payments is july 31 and no change in the repayment date is likely 
this time 
the deadline already has been put off three times and sen kent 
conrad dnd tried unsuccessfully this spring to get congress to 
forgive the debt for some farmers who faced drought again this year 
its something kent tried very very hard to accomplish but 
wasnt able to do so said conrads press secretary laurie 
boeder 
county offices of the agricultural stabilization and 
conservation service are to send notices later this month to the 
farmers who owe the refunds said ascs spokesman ray wagoner 
each spring the agriculture department will advance to farmers 
40 percent of the deficiency payments they expect to receive that 
year for wheat corn and other crops in the government farm program 
however if market prices rise during the year as they did 
during 1988 and 1989 and the deficiency payments are smaller than 
projected the farmers are required to refund the overpayments 
usda estimates that farmers who lost crops to the 1988 and 1989 
droughts owe 403 million in refunds corn growers owe 210 million 
and wheat producers owe 89 million 
conrad who believes the total is more like 200 million tried 
twice in may to amend an emergency appropriations bill to write off 
the 308 million in refunds he predicted would be owed by farmers 
who are likely to go through drought again this year 
the forgiveness would have applied only to advances that farmers 
received for crops that were never produced because of the drought 
farmers would still owe refunds on crops they produced 
many of these people virtually have no opportunity to pay back 
the advanced deficiency payments which they have received said 
sen tom daschle dsd during one of the debates 
in arguing for his amendment conrad said there probably would 
not be another bill that could reach the presidents desk in time 
to beat the deadline 
hes still looking for a vehicle that might get through the 
process in time boeder said this week 
