have difficulties and shortages but the foreigner has never solved 
our troubles 
under 45 years of hardline communist rule travel for average 
albanians has been virtually impossible as the countrys late 
leader enver hoxha steered his 32 million people into increasing 
isolation 
but under alia who took over after hoxhas death in 1985 the 
country has increasingly sought ties abroad and has begun 
implementing some cautious reforms 
alia has given no hint the leadership was considering any form 
of political plurality of the kind now in place in formerly 
monolithic communist countries in europe 
alia pledged continued reforms friday but said only the 
communist party could realize the genuine democracy the human 
rights the countrys progress and the defense of its freedom and 
independence 
he promised a new election law but strongly implied it would 
not affect the communist partys monopoly on power the meeting 
will continue saturday 
the rush on the embassies continued friday even after the 
government repeated a pledge to issue travel documents for everyone 
seeking to leave the country 
many albanians with passports and exit visas were seeking entry 
visas from the various embassies some came and left during the 
day others mistrustful of their governments pledges joined 
those already holed up for days said diplomats 
the diplomats speaking on condition of anonymity said 
conditions were getting worse inside some of the embassies 
west german officials in bonn said well over 1000 
asylumseekers were in their tirana embassy an employee of the 
italian embassy in tirana said the number there had grown to 700 by 
evening other officials said the french embassy held 400 and the 
polish and czechoslovak embassies about 50 each 
authorities have rebuffed attempts by foreign governments to 
send supplies 
refugees began fleeing into the west german embassy on sunday 
night albanian guards shot and wounded two of them that night the 
bonn foreign ministry said it said from 30 to 40 asylumseekers 
were injured monday night as they crashed their truck into the west 
german compound to gain entry 
an italian embassy employee reached from rome described the 
situation on the crowded embassy grounds as more tragic than 
comic this is an embassy designed for 10 people you can 
imagine what conditions are like 
apa said embassies were growing short of food and medicine 
a hungarian diplomat describing the situation in the 
neighboring french mission said it was jammed with many sleeping 
in the embassy garden 
the sometimes violent rush to the embassies follows last years 
exodus of east germans to embassies in other east european 
countries shortly before the fall of east germanys hardline 
government 
the albanian foreign ministry on thursday promised to grant 
passports to those who have sought refuge in foreign embassies in a 
desperate attempt to flee their homeland 
hundreds more continued to gather outside embassies and gained 
entry to embassy compounds 
west german and hungarian diplomats said police were not 
preventing people from approaching their embassies and were 
allowing relatives to talk to the refugees through embassy compound 
fences 
a package of new regulations entitling all albanians over the 
age of 16 to own a passport for foreign travel took effect 
tuesday it did not check the flow of asylumseekers 
most of the albanians who fled to foreign embassies before 
thursday entered in a rush during rioting that began monday under 
fire from albanian security forces diplomats said at least three 
people were wounded 
ata denied there were casualties 
