the nations leadership friday 
warned the republic of slovenia to abandon its declaration of 
regional autonomy saying it threatens yugoslavias federation 
the countrys eightmember presidential council said it will 
take all measures to protect the integrity and sovereignty of 
yugoslavia the state news agency tanjug reported however the 
announcement did not elaborate 
slovenias new freely elected legislature proclaimed its 
autonomy on monday the move was viewed as a further challege to 
yugoslavias fragile communistruled federation 
the authority of the federal leadership has effectively been 
crippled since noncommunist centerright parties won elections 
this year in slovenia and croatia another liberal republic it was 
the first free balloting in yugoslavia in 50 years 
slovenia and croatia are demanding a looser national 
confederation 
the current federation of six republics and two autonomous 
provinces already allows each region to run its own government and 
communist party structure 
the decentralized system of government was devised by the late 
national leader josip broz tito in the 1974 constitution the 
arrangement was intended to prevent one republic from gaining sway 
over the others but ethnic and economic differences are again 
threatening the countrys unity 
in its statement friday the presidencial council said the 
slovenian declaration jeopardizes collective yugoslav interests 
and the countrys position in the world 
the slovenian declaration calls for the establishment of an 
independent legal system that would take precedence over federal 
laws it also says slovenian authorities should assert control over 
all armed forces stationed on the republics territory 
 
