<TEXT>
the state bought its first 10acre 
parcel of land friday for construction of the superconducting super 
collider a mammoth 8 billion atom smasher 
more than 16000 acres still have to be acquired from more than 
700 ellis county landowners just south of dallas for the worlds 
largest scientific instrument 
the collider will be a 54mile underground ring in which 
protons will be accelerated to nearly the speed of light while 
superconducting magnets force them to travel a circle two groups 
of protons will be smashed together scientists hope the resulting 
wreckage of subatomic particles will offer new clues to the 
fundamentals of matter 
the first parcel was sold by retired banker er tut morris and 
his wife tommie morris of the dallas suburb of balch springs for 
45000 
the morrises drew applause when they removed a contract 
pending banner from a sign revealing contract sold 
underneath 
i think its a good thing for the history of the us and for 
ellis county and dallas county said morris were very pleased 
with the price 
the land was purchased for the state by the texas national 
research laboratory commission which proposed the ellis county 
site for the collider to the us department of energy 
ownership eventually will be transferred to the federal 
government 
the government is expected to spend 40 million to 100 million 
for 10000 acres of land and rights to the land underneath an 
additional 7000 acres acquisition is expected to be completed in 
1992 
phillip stafford associate director for site development said 
the commission hasnt yet encountered landowners unwilling to sell 
the process anticipates that there will be those who may not 
be a willing seller stafford said our commission and other 
state agencies or federal agencies have the power of eminent domain 
to ensure the project is not held up for those reasons 
hoyt gaston who owns 100 acres says hell be willing to sell 
if the price is right 
ill be satisfied if i get a deal as good as morris got 
he said gaston is expecting an appraisal on his land in about a 
month 
in may the house voted to build the collider and limited the 
federal governments share in the giant science project to 5 
billion 
costs above 5 billion would be left to texas which has pledged 
1 billion and other sources including foreign investors 
the collider scheduled to be completed in 1998 is expected to 
provide 4500 jobs during construction and 2500 permanently 
