<TEXT>
three crippled monkeys the subject of 
court fights by animal rights activists for nine years were 
humanely put to death friday after final experiments involving 
sensory perception officials said 
the three monkeys were among seven remaining animals seized from 
a silver spring md laboratory in 1981 they were part of a study 
of stroke and spinal cord injury rehabilitation financed by the 
national institutes of health researchers had cut the sensory 
nerves to the animals left arms 
the silver spring monkeys have been kept at tulane universitys 
delta regional primate research center since they were seized by 
the government 
the way for the final experiments was cleared tuesday when a 
federal appeals court in washington rejected attempts by the 
physicians committee for responsible medicine to save them 
each monkey was put under deep surgical anesthesia said tulane 
medical center spokeswoman debbie grant while asleep electrodes 
were inserted in their brains to monitor signals produced when 
parts of the body were touched 
it was the same as the experiment performed on another silver 
spring monkey in january to test a theory that parts of the brain 
that are no longer used for one function might take over other 
functions 
the nerve endings to the monkeys arms were severed nine years 
ago in a study of stroke and spinal cord injury rehabilitation the 
researchers wanted to know whether the part of the brain that was 
no longer used to sense feeling in the arms would start responding 
to stimuli on other parts of the body 
in the january experiment the unused part of the brain was 
found to respond when other parts of the body were touched the 
results of fridays experiments were not immediately known 
after the experiment while the monkeys were asleep they were 
put to death by lethal injection ms grant said no pain was 
involved 
conducting the experiments were tim pons of the national 
institutes of health and preston garraghty of vanderbilt university 
the decision for euthanasia was made because of the monkeys 
physical condition ms grant said unable to feel pain they had 
bitten and otherwise injured their arms sometimes severely 
the monkeys had been at the center of controversy since an 
animal rights group claimed they were being mistreated in 
experiments sponsored by the nih that led to the silver spring 
raid and charges of animal cruelty against dr edward taub whose 
conviction was overturned on appeal 
