<TEXT>
the manager of the hanford nuclear 
reservation resigned friday to move to the private sector saying 
hed peaked in government work and that a better job didnt exist 
within the us department of energy 
mike lawrence said he had accepted a betterpaying job with 
chemnuclear environmental systems of denver a branch of giant 
waste management inc 
no successor was immediately named to head hanford which has 
14000 employees and a 1 billion annual budget and which for four 
decades has made plutonium for nuclear weapons 
lawrence long a controversial figure in the department because 
of his openness with the public said he was not forced out of the 
position he has held since 1984 
now is the time to leave government service said lawrence 
42 i have peaked in that i have no place to go in government 
chemnuclear is a federal contractor for nuclear waste cleanup 
and environmental restoration lawrence said he would be director 
of waste management 
i will continue in an area i enjoy with people i have 
respect for lawrence said 
his resignation is effective july 28 and he will move with his 
family to the denver area in august lawrence told a news 
conference 
catherine kaliniak an energy department spokeswoman in 
washington dc said the agency would have no comment on 
lawrences resignation 
lawrence earned 83600 per year as one of does nine field 
managers he declined to disclose his salary with the new company 
but said it was a substantial raise 
government regulations will prevent him from working with 
hanford projects for up to one year and in some cases for much 
longer lawrence said 
lawrence insisted that his relations with the energy department 
hierarchy remained good and that he had not been asked to find a 
new job 
us rep sid morrison rwash who represents the hanford 
area said lawrence had been on the cutting edge of does new 
policy of openness and that had caused problems 
wed known for some time that mike was uncertain of his status 
with doe and that private enterprise was offering much more than 
the federal government could pay morrison said 
lawrence had consistently earned high marks from government 
regulators and antinuclear activists 
he recently touched off protests by disclosing that some of 
hanfords nuclear waste storage tanks could explode although he 
stressed the risk was low 
lawrence said friday that he was proud of last years triparty 
agreement a pact between doe the environmental protection agency 
and the state of washington that set up a 30year timetable for 
cleaning up hanford the nations most contaminated nuclear 
production site 
he said he was also proud of consolidating the hanford site from 
eight contractors to four in the mid1980s and for stressing 
safety over production 
