<TEXT>
after 15 years of guerrilla war east 
timor nationalists have added street protests to their campaign for 
independence in the former portuguese colony seized by indonesia 
in the mountains rebels snipe at government soldiers in one of 
the worlds leastknown insurgencies dating from the indonesian 
invasion in 1975 
many timorese apparently have accepted being part of indonesia 
but militants in the mainly roman catholic territory fiercely 
oppose rule by the predominantly moslem country 
young independence activists delivered their first public 
message oct 12 during a visit by pope john paul ii 
they surged toward the altar at the end of an outdoor mass 
attended by more than 100000 people shouting slogans and 
unfurling banners several were beaten and 18 detained 
independence demonstrators appeared again when john c monjo 
the us ambassador to indonesia visited east timor in january 
witnesses said several youths were injured by soldiers outside the 
hotel turismo 
at least one other public protest has has been reported since 
both government officials and rebel spokesmen confirm the 
nationalist tactics are changing 
mario v carrascalao the provincial governor said more 
demonstrations could be expected 
he said no more than 40 activists were involved during the 
popes visit about 200 turned out when monjo was in dili and we 
let them walk around for three days carrascalao siad in an 
interview 
a human rights organization said at least 25000 indonesian 
soldiers had moved into east timor for cleanup operations 
against guerrillas ahead of a visit by portuguese officials in 
september 
since february troop strength has been brought to 40000 from 
about 15000 said carmel budiarjo director of campaign tapol a 
group based in london that focuses on indonesia 
carrascalao the provincial governor said he anticipated 
demonstrations during the portuguese visit 
abilio araujo leader of the fretilin resistance movement told 
reporters in lisbon in february this year we plan to step up 
organized mass resistance in occupied territories we cant 
defeat indonesia militarily but they will never eradicate us 
either 
fretilin is a portuguese acronym for the leftist revolutionary 
front for an independent east timor a bid for power by the 
fretilin movement after portuguese officials fled a coup attempt in 
august 1975 gave indonesia the excuse to invade from west timor 
its half of the island 
indonesia annexed east timor as its 27th province in 1976 but 
the united nations still recognizes portugal as the administering 
power the portuguese closed their embassy in jakarta after the 
invasion and dutch diplomats look after portuguese interests in 
indonesia 
the united states recognized indonesias incorporation of east 
timor without acknowledging it was a valid act of 
selfdetermination a us embassy official said 
east timor one of the worlds leastdeveloped areas is on the 
eastern end of the indonesian archipelago 1300 miles from jakarta 
and only 350 from australias northwest coast 
it is blessed by balmy breezes and beautiful beaches but is no 
idyllic tropical isle 
inhospitable brown mountains are cut by parched valleys sparse 
vegetation and scars left by slashandburn farming make the 
highlands seem desolate the earth is cracked in the dry season and 
flooded when rains come 
per capita annual income was the equivalent of 40 in 1974 and 
now is 200 east timor has no industry only a tiny service sector 
and bleak prospects for those seeking work 
little information about the insurgency has been available 
because indonesia virtually sealed off east timor after annexing 
it east timorese were not allowed out and only a few foreigners 
got in with official permission 
farming stopped and starvation spread 
east timor faced disaster for a time it was averted by 
emergency food supplies starting in 1979 from the international 
committee of the red cross and catholic relief services of the 
united states 
critics claim thousands of lives could have been saved if 
indonesia and permitted relief operations earlier 
how many people died is not known 
in 1985 the human rights group amnesty international said 
200000 people may have died from all causes roman catholic 
clergymen estimate the total at more than 100000 and diplomats in 
jakarta say 60000 there are no official figures 
east timors population was given as 552954 in the 1980 census 
compared to the last colonial portuguese estimate of 635000 
carrascalao said the population now was 695000 
we are still in a period of transition said the provincial 
governor a native of timor who was an official of the colonial 
administration he estimated 5 to 10 percent of the people opposed 
integration with indonesia 
the 450 years of portuguese rule made us different even from 
people on the other half of the island he said west timor was 
part of the dutch east indies until indonesia won independence in 
1949 
carrascalao described the demonstrations as attempts by a very 
small minority to provoke the armed forces 
they are young high school graduates who cannot find jobs 
he said once educated they dont want to be farmers 
in lisbon fretilin spokesman jose guterres said the opposite 
its not that they are doing this because they dont want to be 
farmers its a political thing 
he said the protesters belonged to a clandestine group formed by 
the rebels in 1980 
hundreds of schools built by indonesia since annexation helped 
reduce illiteracy from more than 90 percent in colonial days to 31 
carrascalao said 
guterres acknowledged the new schools helped increase literacy 
but added only indonesian is taught indonesian language 
culture values ours are totally ignored the only way we learn 
them is at home in the family 
at carrascalaos prodding indonesia opened east timor in 
january 1989 timorese are free to come and go as they please 
foreigners no longer need permission in visit but must register on 
arrival 
anyone planning to travel outside dili must get a police pass 
that lists both destination and the amount of time allowed there 
officials said there were 6190 tourists last year 
when the dili grapevine identifies foreigners as journalists 
they are approached by timorese who want to talk about their 
plight none would be identified by name 
an unemployed man in his 20s said he was not necessarily in 
favor of fretilin but at least we should be allowed to vote on 
our future 
a teenager lifted his shirt to display multiple scars he said 
were from wounds inflicted by soldiers another insisted the 
atmosphere of terror has intensified since january but gave no 
specifics 
asked how many guerrillas remain carrascalao said i dont 
know exactly a very small number but with high mobility 
guterres who said he fought with the guerrillas before reaching 
portugal two years ago said fretilin had 5000 armed fighters 
plus its own militia within the local population 
indonesian military sources have said for four years the 
guerrillas number about 400 
about 90 percent of indonesias 175 million people are moslems 
but the population of east timor is predominantly catholic early 
last year bishop carlos ximenes belo head of the church in east 
timor urged the united nations to organize a referendum on the 
territorys future 
belo became bishop after his predecessor was forced to resign in 
1983 because church sources said he had criticized conditions 
in east timor 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

