<TEXT>
the administration is apparently looking at 
the securities industry for new taxes prompting trade groups to 
counter with arguments than new levies would drive investors and 
traders overseas 
industry trade groups were responding thursday to word that the 
bush administration is considering an securities transfer excise 
tax of up to 05 percent on the sale of stocks bonds futures 
contracts and other financial products 
countries with securities transaction taxes are now reducing or 
eliminating them the trade groups said 
the taxes have made the countries less competitive with those 
that do not have the taxes the industry leaders said critics of 
transaction taxes in west germany and sweden have blamed them for 
driving away business to other financial centers like london 
it seems to defy common sense to have america embarking on a 
tax now said edward obrien president of the securities 
industry association 
it would be a real shootyourselfinthefoot if we were to 
institute anything like that when our market share is so 
vulnerable said john damgard president of the futures industry 
association 
a treasury spokesman declined to comment on a report in the wall 
street journal thursday that treasury secretary nicholas brady 
and budget director richard darman are said to be intrigued by the 
idea but not committed to it 
congress and the white house are trying to work out a way to cut 
the deficit through a series of negotiations 
the transaction tax was the latest idea to surface since 
president bush stirred things up by ending his read my lips no 
new taxes stance 
congress is not in session this week and most key committee 
aides were not available for comment 
industry officials noted the transaction tax idea is not new 
whats heating this issue up is the fact that suddenly now the 
president is purported to have said everything is on the table so 
every idea that anyones ever had is out there said the futures 
industry associations damgard 
sarah teslik executive director of the council of individual 
investors a group of 65 large pension funds with 300 billion in 
assets said the group has not yet issued an official position on 
the transaction tax 
but ms teslik noted that unlike legislation introduced last 
fall in an effort to curb shortterm trading and market volatility 
the ideas being kicked around do not single out pension funds and 
do not put a time limit on how long a stock must be held to avoid 
taxation 
that type of tax she said would be an administrative nightmare 
for fund managers and could cost pension funds as much as 100 
million a year 
its a bad idea particularly in light of the fact that other 
countries around the world have tried transaction taxes and have 
learned the very difficult lesson that its made them 
noncompetitive said fias damgard 
his claim was echoed by the securities association which 
released study findings that it said showed an independent 
movement underway in many countries to eliminate or reduce the rate 
of transfer taxes for competitive purposes 
of 15 countries surveyed six have either lowered the tax rate 
or are eliminating the tax entirely the sia survey also noted that 
four countries canada greece luxembourg and the united states 
have no transaction tax at all 
last month sias two top officials obrien and robert downey 
the chairman wrote treasury secretary brady asking him to oppose a 
securities transaction tax 
its a universally held view in the industry obrien said 
in a telephone interview thursday if there is some disagreement 
with our position we havent heard it 
he said a tax on transactions could induce individual investors 
to slow up or halt their trading that in turn would lessen 
market liquidity and drive down prices 
</TEXT>
