<TEXT>
amid us pressure on japan to open its rice 
market the government friday decided to cut by only 15 percent 
the price it will pay to rice farmers this year 
the price cut is the first in two years but it is much less 
than some government officials had hoped for to end us criticism 
of japans rice market which is virtually closed to imports 
an earlier plan by the agriculture ministry to cut the price 
paid to farmers for their rice crops by about 5 percent was killed 
when it was opposed by members of the ruling liberal democratic 
party who depend heavily on farmer support the party had 
requested a freeze on the price 
the government regulates and subsidizes the domestic rice 
market buying much of the rice crop and reselling it to consumers 
at lower prices 
the subsidy cost the government 3117 billion yen or 208 
billion in fiscal 1989 the 15 percent reduction is expected to 
help cut the budget by about 9 billion yen or 60 million 
japanese rice is about four times more expensive than us rice 
japans rice market is likely to be on the agenda at next weeks 
summit of seven major industrialized nations in houston texas 
producer prices were cut by 595 percent in 1987 and by 46 
percent in 1988 they remained unchanged last year when the ruling 
party faced national elections 
japan has been criticized for its rice ban during the current 
uruguay round of multilateral trade talks under the general 
agreement on tariffs and trade 
but the nation has insisted on maintaining selfsufficiency for 
rice its staple food limited quantities of rice are imported for 
use in processed foods 
agriculture minister tomio yamamoto is adamantly opposed to 
opening the rice market 
there are signs however that some japanese would welcome a 
more flexible position on rice imports 
the secondlargest opposition party recently endorsed easing the 
ban on imports and former prime minister noboru takeshita praised 
the decision as courageous 
last month the paper published a national survey it conducted 
of 2397 eligible voters in may some 65 percent of those polled 
approved of opening japans rice market to some foreign imports 
and 21 percent favorded full liberalization 
</TEXT>
