some labor contractors are cheating 
migrant farm workers by collecting but not reporting 
unemployment and social security taxes an attorney who filed 
federal suits here alleged on friday 
in many cases the contractors fail to report any income by the 
worker leaving them destitute when the season ends or the worker 
retires said james boon of florida legal services inc 
with farm workers unemployment is a very important benefit 
because its a seasonal job and social security is the only 
pension plan these people are ever going to participate in boon 
said it really hurts and its a real serious violation of law 
the suits filed last week allege that farmers in alabama and 
migrant labor crew chiefs based in belle glade withheld thousands 
of dollars in social security and unemployment compensation 
benefits from palm beach county farm workers picking alabamas 
sweet corn crop in june 1986 june 1987 and june 1988 
most of the workers who filed suits are haitian immigrants 
fluent only in their native creole language and are generally 
unfamiliar with us and state labor laws boon said 
he said they are susceptible to abuses by crew chiefs who may 
try to underreport or fail to report the earned wages of farm 
workers 
crew chiefs work as contractors providing the labor to harvest 
fruit and vegetables and package the crops for shipping in 
addition to providing housing and transportation they distribute 
the migrants wages and are responsible for complying with federal 
labor laws 
but boon said only a small number of investigators police the 
crew chiefs 
there is a real big incentive not to report wages especially 
if you dont expect to get in trouble for not doing it he said 
boon said under current laws crew chiefs must set aside 15 for 
each 100 earned by a worker to be contributed as social security 
and about 5 for the state unemployment tax 
the migrants assume the money is sent in but what happens a 
lot of times is that nothing is sent and nothing is reported 
boon said 
