grain and soybean futures prices skidded for the 
second straight day on the chicago board of trade friday as more 
weather forecasters predicted ideal weather next week for 
midwestern crop development and winter wheat harvesting 
the selloff extended thursdays steep losses in the corn and 
soybean markets as it triggered waves of selling by speculators 
earlier this week some private forecasters were predicting hot 
dry weather for the western and southern reaches of the corn belt 
but by friday meteorologists were near unanimous in forecasting 
a week of mild temperatures and beneficial showers for the region 
the corn crop is nearing its pollination phase when heat and 
dryness could reduce yields 
if you dont get a drought at this time of year it means the 
corn crop generally will be developing under favorable 
conditions said katharina zimmer a grains analyst with merrill 
lynch capital markets inc 
the forecasts contained nothing that would adversely affect 
soybeans which reach their pollination phase in august 
and the relatively dry conditions expected in the great plains 
