<TEXT>
the pace of european monetary union is quickening 
bringing closer the day europe will have a single currency and a 
eurofed or central bank 
the result could merge the 12nation european community into one 
mighty economy with a currency rivaling the dollar in world 
importance 
the benefits are obvious travelers no longer would have to 
shuffle lire pesetas pounds francs guilders and crowns 
businesses would be freed from the paperwork and costs linked to 
fluctuating exchange rates 
although ec leaders have agreed to pursue economic and monetary 
union they now are engaged in an intense debate on how to go about 
it 
major unresolved questions include whether the currency would be 
a new monetary unit or a modification of an existing currency 
whether it would replace all 12 common market currencies or become 
a 13th parallel currency and how much power a central monetary 
body would have 
the momentum has considerably increased bertrand de 
maigret secretary general of the parisbased association for the 
monetary union of europe said in an interview 
just a year ago people did not dare talk about a single 
currency he said but now the discussion is full and open 
the july 1 monetary unification of the germanys and the collapse 
of communism in eastern europe have spurred monetary integration 
experts say 
another boost came last month when britain dropped its adamant 
opposition and made a counterproposal to the main monetary union 
plan mapped out by ec commission president jacques delors 
experts now say monetary union could happen by the mid1990s 
peter ludlow head of the center for european policy studies a 
think tank in brussels said use of a single european currency 
could spread to eastern europe and possibly the soviet union 
the dominance of the dollar would be called into question 
he said in an interview 
karl otto poehl president of the german bundesbank or central 
bank said in london on july 3 that he believed ec leaders already 
had reached loose agreement that monetary unity is desirable 
a decision has already been taken to aim for such change 
poehl said citing an agreement by ec leaders in june to discuss 
such matters at an intergovernmental conference in december 
however prime minister margaret thatcher who strongly opposes 
giving up the pound and relinquishing control over britains 
monetary affairs subsequently insisted on retaining the right to 
keep britain out of any full monetary union 
delors has proposed a threestage approach removing trade 
barriers and bringing all 12 ec countries into the 
currencystabilizing exchange rate mechanism a transitional 
period then full monetary union he has set no timetable 
britain says it is committed to the first stage and to the ecs 
plan to remove trade barriers by the end of 1992 and create one 
marketplace of 320 million people 
britain portugal and greece presently are outside the exchange 
rate mechanism 
delors advocates using the european currency unit or ecu a 
10yearold instrument made up of a basket of european currencies 
to replace the existing currencies the ecu already exists but is 
used mostly for accounting among countries 
poehl said the german mark or some other common currency must be 
at the core of any eventual monetary unity and that the eurofed 
should control its exchange rates 
while he said west germany might agree to give up the use of the 
mark under such a plan he rejected the ecu as a substitute 
west germany also has suggested twospeed monetary union under 
which it would join france belgium the netherlands and luxembourg 
in moving quickly toward monetary union while other ec nations 
come in later delors rejects this 
britain made its counterproposal on june 21 calling for the 
current ecu to be turned into a hard currency to be used alongside 
the existing 12 
a new institution called the european monetary fund would swap 
new ecu bank notes for european currencies thus minimizing any 
threat of inflation from pumping out new money the ecu would not 
be allowed to devaluate against other ec currencies 
in the very long term if peoples and governments so choose 
it could develop into a single currency says britains top 
treasury official chancellor of the exchequer john major 
delors and poehl said the idea should be studied but continued 
to press their own positions 
one possibility is that the british plan might become a phase 
toward full monetary union 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

