<TEXT>
gov michael s dukakis signed a law friday that 
will open massachusetts borders to banks from other regions while 
trying to combat racial bias in lending 
the bill not only guarantees that every bank in the 
commonwealth meets the needs of all its customers but encourages 
those banks to compete in both national and international financial 
markets dukakis said 
interstate banking has been billed as a potential boon to the 
slumping state economy as more outofstate banks could bring new 
capital to massachusetts 
but analysts and representatives of the banking industry said 
friday they did not expect immediate changes 
i dont see any rush to come here said james moynihan a 
banking analyst with advest inc the profitability of new 
england banks is very poor the companies are not very sought 
after for now 
nonetheless robert sheridan of the massachusetts bankers 
association said it was important for massachusetts to make this 
move currently 26 states allow national interstate banking and 
seven more are scheduled to join the ranks within two years 
according to the bankers association 
until now massachusetts allowed interstate banking only on a 
regional basis the bill will take effect in 60 days but banks can 
opt out of the provisions until july 1 1992 if twothirds of the 
board of directors agree 
the community reinvestment provisions of the law will require 
the state to publicize the ratings banks receive based on their 
lending to minorities and lowincome people 
</TEXT>
