<TEXT>
the dollar finished mixed on domestic currency 
markets friday after closing higher overseas following the release 
of a betterthanexpected us unemployment report 
gold prices also ended mixed on new yorks commodity exchange 
gold bullion for current delivery slipped 30 cents from late 
wednesday to settle at 36110 a troy ounce republic national bank 
in new york quoted a late bid for gold at 36020 down 30 cents 
despite a continuing slump in the nations manufacturing and 
construction sectors the unemployment rate fell to 52 percent in 
june from 53 percent the previous month the labor department 
reported 
many traders had expected unemployment to shoot up as high as 
55 percent a move that could have encouraged the federal reserve 
to ease interest rates to stimulate a flagging economy 
the report however dispelled some anticipation that the fed 
might ease said ronald holzer chief dealer at harris trust and 
savings bank in chicago higher interest rates make 
dollardenominated securities more attractive and thereby enhance 
foreign investors needs for dollars to buy debt instruments 
nonfarm payrolls increased by 40000 jobs in june far lower 
than market expectations but linda mclaughlin a trader at 
chemical new york capital markets group said the fact that the 
overall unemployment rate fell generated enough interest in the 
dollar to override the impact of the payroll figure 
the dollar rose overseas but turned mixed when trading shifted 
to the united states dealers said however that the 
muchanticipated employment report failed to move the market 
significantly and activity was relatively thin 
in tokyo the dollar closed at 15095 yen down 005 yen from 
thursdays close later in london the dollar was quoted higher at 
15100 yen in new york the dollar settled at 15170 yen up from 
15057 yen on thursday 
the british pound rose to 17865 from late thursdays 17795 
in new york one pound cost 17865 more expensive than 17815 on 
thursday 
