<TEXT>
grain and soybean futures prices plunged for the second straight 
day friday as more weather forecasters predicted ideal weather next 
week for midwestern crop development and winter wheat harvesting 
on other commodity markets pork futures fell sharply copper 
futures climbed precious metals slipped and energy futures were 
mixed 
on the chicago board of trade wheat futures settled 5 cents to 
10 cents lower with the contract for delivery in july at 309 a 
bushel corn was 3 cents to 8 cents lower with july at 280 a 
bushel oats were 4 cents to 5 cents lower with july at 131 a 
bushel soybeans were 8 cents to 10 cents lower with july at 619 
a bushel 
the selloff extended thursdays steep losses in the corn and 
soybean markets as it triggered waves of selling by speculators 
earlier this week some private forecasters were predicting hot 
dry weather for the western and southern reaches of the corn belt 
but by friday theyre all saying the weathers going to be 
mild with good rain in the next week or so and that is the ball 
game said victor lespinasse an assistant vice president in the 
grain trading division of dean witter reynolds inc 
after the close the national weather service issued a new 
sixto10day forecast predicting normal temperatures and rainfall 
in the midwest during the period july 1216 
the corn crop is nearing its pollination phase when heat and 
dryness could reduce yields 
if you dont get a drought at this time of year it means the 
corn crop generally will be developing under favorable 
conditions said katharina zimmer a grains analyst with merrill 
lynch capital markets inc 
the forecasts contained nothing that would adversely affect 
soybeans which reach their pollination phase in august 
and the relatively dry conditions expected in the great plains 
should allow winter wheat harvesting to accelerate 
pork futures tumbled on the chicago mercantile exchange on 
selling linked to recent high hog slaughter figures and sluggish 
retail demand especially for bacon 
the agriculture departments hog slaughter estimates of 293000 
head thursday and 285000 friday were both about 15000 head higher 
than market expectations the high slaughter rates have increased 
supplies of all pork including the bellies from which bacon is 
made 
the heavy slaughter is not alarming but its enough to put 
people on edge said dale durchholz an analyst with agrivisor 
services inc in bloomington ill 
cattle futures were boosted in part by expectations for rising 
retail demand for beef 
live cattle settled 12 cent to 63 cent higher with august at 
7365 cents a pound feeder cattle were 25 cent to 80 cent higher 
with august at 8455 cents a pound live hogs were 28 cent to 125 
cents higher with july at 6160 cents a pound frozen bellies for 
july and august delivery fell the permitted daily limit of 2 cents 
a pound with july settling at 5417 cents other belly contracts 
were 10 cent lower to 43 cent higher 
copper futures settled 07 cent to 25 cents higher on new 
yorks commodity exchange reflecting increasing worries about 
supply availability 
a strike at asarco incs ray copper mine in arizona stretched 
into its sixth day friday futures also were supported by news that 
production from the chilean copper cos el teniente mine would 
drop by 18000 metric tons this year due to a landslide thursday 
in precious metals trading on the commodity exchange gold 
futures settled 10 cents to 40 cents lower with august at 36290 a 
troy ounce silver was 03 cent to 05 cent lower with july at 
4866 a troy ounce 
petroleum futures were little changed on the new york mercantile 
exchange 
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent to 6 cents 
lower with august at 1647 a barrel heating oil was 09 cent 
lower to 06 cent higher with august at 4830 cents a gallon 
unleaded gasoline was 20 cent to 46 cent higher with august at 
5541 cents a gallon 
